<h2><a name="download" id="download">Can I download e-mail
addresses for Eudora, Outlook or Netscape mail?</a></h2>

Yes, here are some instructions.

<h3>Microsoft Outlook Express</h3>

<ol>
<li>Go to the <a href="/ghs/download/">Download Nickname and
Address Book Files</a> page.
<li>In the Format section, select "Microsoft&nbsp;Outlook&nbsp;.CSV".
<li>Click the "Download" button. 
<li>When prompted, specify a convenient location and name for the .CSV
file in the "Save As" dialog box.
<li>Open Microsoft Outlook Express.
<li>Select "Address Book" from the Tools menu to launch the Windows
Address Book.
<li>In the Address Book window, use the File menu to select
"Import-&gt;Address&nbsp;Book."
<li>Select the file type "Text File (Comma Separated Values)." 
<li>Click the "Import" button.
<li>Enter or browse for the file you just created, then click the "Next"
button.
<li>Uncheck any fields you do not wish to import to Outlook Express or
click "Change Mapping..." to modify the destination in Outlook Express
where your Alumni Internet Directory data will be stored.
<li>Click "Finish" to import the data. 
</ol>

<h3>Microsoft Outlook 97, 98, or 2000</h3>

<ol>
<li>Go to the <a href="/ghs/download/">Download Nickname and
Address Book Files</a> page.
<li>In the Format section, select "Microsoft&nbsp;Outlook&nbsp;.CSV".
<li>Click the "Download" button. 
<li>When prompted, specify a convenient location and name for the .CSV
file in the "Save As" dialog box.
<li>Open Microsoft Outlook 97, 98, or 2000.
<li>Select the "Go/Contacts" option. 
<li>Open the File menu and select "Import and Export." 
<li>Select "Import from another program or file" and click "Next."
<li>Select "Comma Separated Values (Windows)" and click "Next."
<li>Find the desired CSV file, select "Do not import duplicate items, "
and click "Next."
<li>Select the Contacts folder and click "Next."  
<li>Click "Finish" to confirm.  This will import your chosen file.
</ol>

<h3>Netscape Address Book</h3>

<ol>
<li>Go to the <a href="/ghs/download/">Download Nickname and
Address Book Files</a> page.
<li>In the Format section, select "Netscape&nbsp;4.x&nbsp;.LDIF".
<li>Click the "Download" button.
<li>When prompted, specify a convenient location and name for the .LDIF
file in the "Save As" dialog box.
<li>Open Netscape Communicator version 4.0 or greater.
<li>Under the Communicator menu, select "Address Book." 
<li>In the "Address Book" window, open the File menu and select "Import."
<li>Find the file and choose "Open."  This will import the chosen file.
</ol>

