<h2><a name="bounces" id="bounces">What happens to invalid e-mail
addresses?</a></h2>

<p>When e-mail to a alumnus bounces, I determine (by hand) whether
it's a temporary problem (such as their mail spool being full) or
whether their account doesn't exist anymore. If the latter is the
case, their record is moved to the <a
href="/ghs/invalid.html">invalid e-mail addresses</a> page. If
someone asks to be removed from the database, I just nuke their
record altogether.</p>

<p><br><br></p>

<h2><a name="vcard" id="vcard">What's a vCard?</a></h2>

<p>The vCard, a creation of the <a
href="http://www.imc.org/"> Internet
Mail Consortium</a>, is an electronic business card.  Support for vCard
viewing is built into Netscape Communicator 4.x.  To view a vCard on
Netscape 3, and Internet Explorer 3, you can <a
href="http://www.nowsoft.com/plugins/about_people.html">download the
plugin from Now Software</a>.  For IE4 and above, you can use Microsoft
Outlook or the Windows Address Book to view vCards.  For more technical
information on vCard, see the IMC's <a
href="http://www.imc.org/pdi/vcardoverview.html">vCard overview</a>.</p>

<p><br><br></p>

<h2><a name="yab" id="yab">What is Yahoo! Address Book?</a></h2>

<p>To quote the official propaganda provided by Yahoo! (<a
href="http://help.yahoo.com/help/ab/ab-01.html">http://help.yahoo.com/help/ab/ab-01.html</a>):</p>

<blockquote><a
href="http://address.yahoo.com/">Yahoo! Address
Book</a> is a powerful online contact manager. Similar to a paper
or desktop address book, it can also do many things they can't. Use
it to store all your contact information about individuals and
companies. Since it's online, you can access it with an Internet
connection from anywhere in the world. No more worrying about
losing or leaving behind your paper address book or electronic
organizer.</blockquote>

<p>You'll need to be a registered Yahoo! user (it's free) in order
to use Address Book and Yahoo!'s personalized services. You must be
logged into Yahoo! to use the "add to Y! address book" links on the
Directory pages, or else it will prompt you to log in.</p>

